t4715.text: I don't get paid for it. I don't coach my own kids. I don't want to get paid for it. But if I did decide I wanted to become a professional coach, I would need to coach age groups outside of my strength, or start my own private basketball coaching business.

t4716.text: My eldest at this stage doesn't have much interest in basketball, but cricket is another story (thank you @MollyStrano). I also played a few games of "rep" cricket as a kid, so may need to go down the cricket coaching route soon! The point is, coaching is my volunteer career.

t4717.text: And teach them how to dribble both hands, pass the ball, play as a team, defend man to man, because some of the adults I was coaching at the time couldn't do that! I had no kids to work around at this age. Now I've got 2 kids under 5, and rep coaching is out due to time.

t4718.text: At this age, the kids are sponges, they're a lot more fun and you are hopefully teaching them good habits for the rest of their lives. I once had a stint coaching a youth u23 rep side early on in my career, but after 2 years realised I needed to go back to the kids 3/?

t4719.text: But I've always headed back to the familiar territory of u10 & U12 boys. Irony is, no one wants to coach this level, especially those with career progression in mind, but this is the age you set them up for life, both in the sport and out of sport. To me, it's more rewarding. 2/?
